00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:51.900
What I was gonna do today is, is talk about
a, a sort of grand synthesis of the work that

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:57.530
we've been doing since we went into business
in 2000 and, and then to explore ideas about

00:04:57.530 --> 00:05:02.150
how we can move forward, not only with our
survey work but with this computational research.

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:09.650
The big idea that we've sort of pulled together,
thanks to our, our research and, and readings

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:15.560
in, in other areas, is that people have moved
in their social structures from a position

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:21.840
of sort of tight-knit, bounded social relationships
where they live in small communities that

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:26.680
everybody knows your business and everybody
knows everybody else's business and everybody

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:30.730
knows each other. That's the world the villages,
the tight-knit families, and even tight-knit

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:36.170
workplaces. The argument that we see emerging
in our data, and it began to emerge even before

00:05:36.170 --> 00:05:41.720
the technology revolutions that we are under,
is that the world has moved more towards networks.

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:46.250
A colleague of mine, who matter of fact I'm
writing a book with him, a sociologist at

00:05:46.250 --> 00:05:50.810
the University of Toronto named Barry Wellman,
has talked about life in the latter half of

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:55.050
the 20th century and the emerging part of
the 21st century as being lived in a state

00:05:55.050 --> 00:06:00.170
of networked individualism where we've moved
from these tight-knit groups, where we get

00:06:00.170 --> 00:06:04.280
our social support and our care and feeding
and nurturing in the world, to more networking

00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:09.070
behavior where we can maneuver a little bit
more easily through more dispersed networks

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:14.419
and more kinds of social relations. But we
pay some pr-, prices for that social change

00:06:14.419 --> 00:06:17.260
that I'll talk about later.

00:06:17.260 --> 00:06:21.850
Before I get to the technology piece of this
I will just run through a couple of big social

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:26.450
and political trends that are already driving
culture towards networked individualism, which

00:06:26.450 --> 00:06:30.510
means that people have more power themselves
to be their own individual actors, or people

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:34.730
are forced to be their own individual actors
because social structures around them that

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:38.980
were built on that tight-knit networks were,
were changing.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:43.090
The first big change, of course, is affluence
and technology itself. Th-, it's put in to

00:06:43.090 --> 00:06:48.430
our hands, particularly in the developed world,
a sense that we can do more things on our

00:06:48.430 --> 00:06:54.770
own. We can array, we can use media, we can
use o-, other tools at our disposal to do

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:59.520
things that it used to take larger groups
of people and collectives to perform.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:03.780
The second thing is that family composition
itself has forced people to be networkers,

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:08.620
as roles inside families have become even
more networked themselves. Think about each

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:14.610
spouse has his or her own address book, his
or h- own professional network to deal with,

00:07:14.610 --> 00:07:21.520
his or h-, own, his or her own social networks
to deal with when they have troubles in their

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:22.520
lives.

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:26.380
Families themselves have become networks and
so people even inside their own households

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:30.940
have now had to take more responsibility on
for managing their own lives and, and, and

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:35.400
engaging the world in their own ways. There's
obviously been a proliferation of consumer

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:39.270
choice in the world. We have to make more
choices and we want to make more choices as,

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:43.720
as the array of stuff that enters our life
and the array of services has grown, so we

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:46.730
have to be active agents in exploring all
of that.

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:51.061
Income and wealth volatility have increased
in, in particularly in America in the past

00:07:51.061 --> 00:07:56.100
two generations. Job security and job longevity
have decreased; we're cycling through more

00:07:56.100 --> 00:08:00.220
jobs doing more things with ups and downs
in our wealth status, ups and downs in our

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:04.940
income status. We just have to be on top of
more things. The old social contract, as you

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:10.419
know, about somebody l-locking in with an
employer at age 19, living with that employer

00:08:10.419 --> 00:08:16.010
to age 60 or 65, having all his or her needs
met by that employer during the period of

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:20.300
employment and then even post-employment.
That is broken down now in the age of multiple

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:26.700
careers, m-massive churn in the job market
and things like that. That's caused a, an

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:28.350
increase in free agency.

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:33.490
There's a wonderful ro-, book written a couple
of years ago by Daniel Pink who talked about

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:37.959
the rise of the number of Americans who were
on their own in the workplace. Sometimes by

00:08:37.959 --> 00:08:42.019
choice, because they had the tools and the
capacity and the knowledge to do it, and because

00:08:42.019 --> 00:08:46.459
they want to do it. They want to be their
own boss. Some people by circumstances that

00:08:46.459 --> 00:08:50.769
were forced on them; they had to add another
income stream to their life so they did things

00:08:50.769 --> 00:08:55.119
after work in their homes, or they tried to
sell things on the weekend, or they developed

00:08:55.119 --> 00:08:58.279
an EBay or Amazon cont-, account to sell things.

00:08:58.279 --> 00:09:04.351
Overall, Pink added up in about 2001-2002
that there were 35 million people who were

00:09:04.351 --> 00:09:08.699
sole proprietors working on their own businesses
or working in very small family businesses

00:09:08.699 --> 00:09:13.089
that it, that was a doubling of the number
who were in free agency kinds of situations

00:09:13.089 --> 00:09:17.639
a decade before. And there are probably more
still now since we've churned through a recession

00:09:17.639 --> 00:09:22.639
now that is forcing more people to act as
their own agents or supplement their work

00:09:22.639 --> 00:09:27.709
life with other kinds of things that they
do on their own.

00:09:27.709 --> 00:09:31.619
There's been a big change in, in employer
relationships with employees where now employees

00:09:31.619 --> 00:09:35.809
have to take more care of their healthcare
and of their own pensions. Again, when in,

00:09:35.809 --> 00:09:40.230
in that lifetime guarantee of work situation,
the employer would provide the pension, you

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:43.649
served your time in the company, you went
out and the-, and the company kept sending

00:09:43.649 --> 00:09:44.649
you checks.

00:09:44.649 --> 00:09:47.590
That is no longer the case for the majority
of Americans. They have to manage their own

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:51.089
retirement, they have to think about their
own investments, and they have to plan for

00:09:51.089 --> 00:09:54.999
them in ways. So that's forced them to fall
back again into individual strategies rather

00:09:54.999 --> 00:09:57.860
than group strategies to manage their stuff.

00:09:57.860 --> 00:10:02.709
And then finally there is sort of bigger social
ch-, changes outside the realms of, of, of

00:10:02.709 --> 00:10:08.139
people's personal lives that have also prompted
them to become more independent actors in

00:10:08.139 --> 00:10:12.550
the world rather than group actors in the
world. I call this sort of D-I-Y, Do It Yourself

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:17.689
politics and religion even. In a, in colleagues
work that, that's done by the Pew Research

00:10:17.689 --> 00:10:21.990
Center for the people in the press, they do
a lot of political anal-, analyst and their

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:25.449
just down the hall from us. They live in the
same organization that we do.

00:10:25.449 --> 00:10:28.879
They have charted now, for the first time
in the history of polling, that the largest

00:10:28.879 --> 00:10:33.199
block of voters in this country are self-defined
independents. There are more people who say

00:10:33.199 --> 00:10:37.939
now, "I am independent of political parties,"
than say they are attached to either the Democratic

00:10:37.939 --> 00:10:38.959
or the Republican parties.

00:10:38.959 --> 00:10:43.230
We've never seen this before so again, it
may, it's a trend that pushes people more

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:48.129
towards cobbling together their own political
belief system, their own values and structures,

00:10:48.129 --> 00:10:54.980
rather than affiliating with formal institutions.
In religion, amazingly enough, the same trend

00:10:54.980 --> 00:11:00.119
is taking hold. Forty-four percent of Americans,
in a survey that was done by our colleagues

00:11:00.119 --> 00:11:05.629
at the Pew Religion Forum, have changed the
religion of their childhood in the course

00:11:05.629 --> 00:11:11.430
of their adulthood. So 44% of people in America
now are practicing a religion or connecting

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:16.009
to some kind of faith system that is not the
same one that they grew up with and were taught.

00:11:16.009 --> 00:11:21.040
I, people are again sort of mixing and matching
some other belief systems or they're finding

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:25.449
some other places that serve their needs than
the ones that served their parents. Nobody

00:11:25.449 --> 00:11:30.610
has ever done work like that before so I can't
say that that trend is massively greater than

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:34.660
it was in the past. It's probably pretty typically
American compared to lots of other cultures,

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:39.559
but it still goes to show that there are significant
numbers of people who are sort of making it

00:11:39.559 --> 00:11:43.329
up as they go and acting as, as networked
individuals.

00:11:43.329 --> 00:11:48.699
And finally, even before the Internet and
mobile revolution, but certainly accelerated

00:11:48.699 --> 00:11:53.010
by both those revolutions, there's the DIY
health world that we're in. There are a lot

00:11:53.010 --> 00:11:58.449
more people now that are acting as, as more
aggressively as the agents of their own healthcare.

00:11:58.449 --> 00:12:03.209
They are looking up stuff. In, in the old,
in the pre-Internet days, in all kinds of

00:12:03.209 --> 00:12:06.480
pamphlets and books and magazines and, and
things like that. Now, of course, they're

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:10.410
turning to the Internet to make sense of the
things that have been told to them about what's

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:15.069
wrong with them or even before they've been
diagnosed to try to figure out what's going

00:12:15.069 --> 00:12:18.989
on in their lives and so that they can become
active agents in their own care.

00:12:18.989 --> 00:12:26.361
In a way that you think of the, the pre-Internet
model of the doctor-patient re-, relationship,

00:12:26.361 --> 00:12:31.889
patient has a couple of meanings in America.
The patient was patient. Sort of waited for

00:12:31.889 --> 00:12:36.160
the doctor to decide after a two minute encounter
everything that was wrong with you and prescribe

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:39.739
everything for you, right? Well, the, those
patients are not patient anymore. They're

00:12:39.739 --> 00:12:43.009
going out and they're, they're, they're doing
their own searches and they they're walking

00:12:43.009 --> 00:12:47.389
into doctor's offices with lots of printouts
from the Web and saying, "Why not give me

00:12:47.389 --> 00:12:51.369
this drug?" or, "Why didn't you tell me about
this side effect?" or, "Why didn't you tell

00:12:51.369 --> 00:12:55.329
me about this clinic that is giving a new
experimental treatment on this?"

00:12:55.329 --> 00:12:59.819
So people again are being much more active
in managing the central affairs of their life.

00:12:59.819 --> 00:13:04.279
That's the hallmark of network individualism.
And, of course, technology enters the picture

00:13:04.279 --> 00:13:09.649
and puts everything that has already come
before it on steroids. All of the trends that

00:13:09.649 --> 00:13:15.490
were in evidence in the 1960s, 70s, and 80s,
before the, the Internet was mass adopted

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:21.610
and before mobile phones became staples of
people's lives, are now sort of intensified

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:25.850
in all of these ways. And it's particularly
true of those who are under age 30.

00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:30.860
The people that we call "millennials", the
people who have grown up in a, in respect,

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:36.020
in a world where it was not possible to know
a world without the Internet. And increasingly,

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:40.060
not to know a world without cell phones and
mobile connectivity built into it. People

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:45.989
are now acting as these, as, as networked
individuals in ways that they couldn't have

00:13:45.989 --> 00:13:49.790
before they had these technology tools available
to them.

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:54.720
Quickly, to orient you about the dimensions
of the, of the tech revolution, when we went

00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:58.920
into business, we were sort of in the midway.
We went in to, we did our first survey in

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:05.519
March of 2000, so we were sort of midway through
the mass adoption period of the consumer Internet.

00:14:05.519 --> 00:14:10.971
The first survey we did in March of 2000,
46% of adults used the Internet, 73% of teenagers

00:14:10.971 --> 00:14:18.110
used the Internet. Now, it's 75% of adults
and 93% of teenagers. It's important to remember

00:14:18.110 --> 00:14:22.439
as you are, are thinking about that, that's,
that's an incredible growth story and it's

00:14:22.439 --> 00:14:27.489
an incredible adoption story that in some
sense is unparalleled in, in the sort of mass

00:14:27.489 --> 00:14:32.620
consumer goods, but it's still the case that
25% of Americans don't use the Internet.

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:37.069
They are older, they are less well-educated,
they have fewer resources available to them.

00:14:37.069 --> 00:14:42.059
They are likely to have a handicap, a, a,
or a disability and in America they're much

00:14:42.059 --> 00:14:46.739
less likely to feel comfortable speaking English
as their primary language. We do our survey

00:14:46.739 --> 00:14:50.170
work both in English and Spanish and we ask
at the very beginning, "How would you like

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:54.679
to take the survey?" The people who choose
to take the survey in Spanish are less likely,

00:14:54.679 --> 00:14:58.309
statistically, significantly, to be Internet
users than those who are comfortable with

00:14:58.309 --> 00:14:59.410
English. Yeah?

00:14:59.410 --> 00:15:06.225
&gt;&gt;audience1: Yeah, I was going to ask about
the 7%, not the 25%. What about the 7%--

00:15:06.225 --> 00:15:07.225
&gt;&gt;Lee: The 7--

00:15:07.225 --> 00:15:08.225
&gt;&gt;audience1: of teenagers [inaudible]

00:15:08.225 --> 00:15:10.649
&gt;&gt;Lee: The seven percent of teenagers who
do not use the Internet are mostly lower income

00:15:10.649 --> 00:15:15.259
or rural. Some, some are, have handicaps but
in many cases it's available at their schools

00:15:15.259 --> 00:15:21.540
or local libraries and they just are, aren't
comfortable with it or aren't happy to say

00:15:21.540 --> 00:15:27.249
that they are an Internet user. They often
will use their friends to do key communications

00:15:27.249 --> 00:15:31.319
for them like texting, emailing, or something
like that. They will often have their friends

00:15:31.319 --> 00:15:36.079
do searches for them but they don't classify
themselves as Internet users so it-, there's

00:15:36.079 --> 00:15:39.699
a bit of a knowledge issue; there's definitely
a resource issue. They are poorer than the

00:15:39.699 --> 00:15:43.879
rest of Americans; they're much more likely
to be rural.

00:15:43.879 --> 00:15:48.410
This, this sort of second way that we've seen
