proliferating as people tag content and comment.
And, and when we did some work looking at

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:14.830
how people use news sites and one of the things
we found is that a, a primary marker for people

00:37:14.830 --> 00:37:19.260
of a trustworthy news site now is the ability
to comment and read other people's comments

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:24.300
about news stories. As toxic as they are,
and as incendiary as lots of the commenting

00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:30.310
is on media sites, people still think that
that's now a new element of, of, of trust

00:37:30.310 --> 00:37:33.910
that they have with that organization and,
and, and a willingness of that organization

00:37:33.910 --> 00:37:35.130
to be transparent.

00:37:35.130 --> 00:37:39.190
A lot of people don't care what's on, on the
content of the comments but they like the

00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:43.090
fact that they're there and they like the
fact that there is available interactivity.

00:37:43.090 --> 00:37:48.790
So, what is all this technology done to networks,
particularly to millennials, the people who

00:37:48.790 --> 00:37:53.590
are under 30 and are again living in this
life? For the first, most obvious, thing to

00:37:53.590 --> 00:37:58.880
say about it is that it's made networks more
vivid for people. They actually have a physical

00:37:58.880 --> 00:38:02.380
sense of their social networks that their
parents, their grandparents, and their other

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:08.230
ancestors never had in part because the technology,
in many cases, displays the networks for them

00:38:08.230 --> 00:38:12.290
and allows them to see what is going on and
stay in touch in ways that they never could

00:38:12.290 --> 00:38:18.270
before. So, networks themselves in people's
lives are reified. They're, they're made human

00:38:18.270 --> 00:38:23.800
in ways that they, that they weren't before.
A-, this technology has allowed for immediate

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:26.660
ad hoc creation of networks.

00:38:26.660 --> 00:38:31.510
Maybe you're familiar with the wonderful,
well, two actual wonderful books, Clay Shirky's

00:38:31.510 --> 00:38:37.281
book, "Here Comes Everybody", and Howard Rheingold's
book, "Smart Mobs". People f-, in this environment,

00:38:37.281 --> 00:38:43.280
form networks to them solve problems on the
fly. A lot of times their networks are permanent

00:38:43.280 --> 00:38:47.700
people, but in many cases when people have
a simple need to answer a question, or a simple

00:38:47.700 --> 00:38:52.580
query, or something like that, they will just
sort of ping their network in the broadest

00:38:52.580 --> 00:38:53.580
sense.

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:56.050
They'll post it on Facebook, they'll tw-,
they'll tweet it, they'll stick it on their

00:38:56.050 --> 00:39:00.630
blog and they, and th-, the crowd will answer
their question or, or the crowd will give

00:39:00.630 --> 00:39:06.780
them input and that's, the network assembles
for that purpose and then disbands. And that's

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:11.480
the sort of new function in networks that
is enabled by these technologies. These networks

00:39:11.480 --> 00:39:17.680
have added more segments, as I described before,
especially related to communities of interest.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:22.790
And one of the most striking things, again,
that we see in our health research is the

00:39:22.790 --> 00:39:28.580
power of network, social network segments
that we call, "just in time, just like me"

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:33.180
networks. Where people that have a particular
need… I've just been diagnosed, what's it

00:39:33.180 --> 00:39:37.680
like? Or, I've got a, I've got an appointment
at the doctors. Can someone drive me there?

00:39:37.680 --> 00:39:43.730
I, my child is, has got this. My dad needs
this kind of care. And people, who are, in

00:39:43.730 --> 00:39:48.450
many cases, strangers in, in the right spaces
under the right circumstances, will answer

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:52.530
their questions based on their particular
parallel circumstances.

00:39:52.530 --> 00:39:57.280
There is a special power in that, in networks,
even though it, they might be taking place

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:04.180
between strangers because wer-, when people
are in situations of acute need, they mostly

00:40:04.180 --> 00:40:09.740
like to hear from people who have gone through
the same thing and are mostly like them. So,

00:40:09.740 --> 00:40:15.040
it, it, even more so than family members who
might offer words of comfort, or are trusted

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:20.260
friends like a minister who might offer words
of wisdom or words of counsel, if you can

00:40:20.260 --> 00:40:24.910
find the mother who has gone through has gone
through the exact same thing with roughly

00:40:24.910 --> 00:40:29.730
the same age child that you're going through,
there's a special power and meaning that,

00:40:29.730 --> 00:40:32.070
that is brought out by these new kinds of
networks.

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:40.300
This new technology has made the act of media
making a part of networking activity. Media

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:47.860
now are, are literally active agents in, in
people's networks. I get knowing nods when

00:40:47.860 --> 00:40:52.670
I go out and speak to the world and I speak
to journalistic groups and library groups

00:40:52.670 --> 00:41:00.390
and media companies and, and non-profits of
all kinds when I say," Think about th-, your

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:05.630
networks. Think about this point in the following
way: Do you use Google as a tie or a node

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:06.630
in your network?"

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:07.630
[male voice from audience]

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:11.620
And people will nod yes. That they will, when
they have a need, it's particularly obvious,

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:16.220
it starts with an information query, but if
they know that their network can't solve it

00:41:16.220 --> 00:41:19.690
or if it's something embarrassing that they
don't want to share with their network, or

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:23.740
if it's at a time of day when they don't want
to bother anybody in their network, they will

00:41:23.740 --> 00:41:28.850
turn to the Internet, generically, but often
to a search engine like Google to begin the

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:33.940
process of finding out what's going on, how
can I cope with it, where can I the support

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:34.940
that I need.

00:41:34.940 --> 00:41:41.320
So media itself, the Internet sort of generically,
and search engines in particular, are active

00:41:41.320 --> 00:41:45.410
agents now in people's networks that they
consult as they, as they have done, as people

00:41:45.410 --> 00:41:48.310
have always done with their networks which
is to solve problems, make decisions, and

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:51.490
gain support that they need.

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:58.360
That means that organizations can now be much
more active agents in people's networks than

00:41:58.360 --> 00:42:04.230
they ever used to. And since media now is
personal and social, even organizations that

00:42:04.230 --> 00:42:09.780
are using these media are in people's minds
now; sort of nodes in their networks. If they

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:15.540
have a question they want resolved they are
as happy to turn to a helpful institution

00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:20.160
like a library, like a search engine, like
a non-profit that might be able to give them

00:42:20.160 --> 00:42:24.360
a, r-, information about resources in their
community, and think of that as an active

00:42:24.360 --> 00:42:25.360
agent in their network.

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:28.732
And when we ask people about how they solve
problems and how they get their information

00:42:28.732 --> 00:42:33.970
needs met, we often find that they consult
three or four different types of media, different

00:42:33.970 --> 00:42:40.090
types of people. And media themselves now
are active players in that segmenting of,

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:46.170
of social networking, markets, and information
queries. And finally, the big change, s-,

00:42:46.170 --> 00:42:52.070
one of the big changes in networks that has
been brought upon by, by technology, is that

00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:57.581
consequential strangers and, and that outer
layer of a network can be much more active

00:42:57.581 --> 00:43:01.310
players in people's networks as they are trying
to a-, have questions answered.

00:43:01.310 --> 00:43:04.921
You don't have to know somebody intimately
to ask for their help and in this environment

00:43:04.921 --> 00:43:09.790
get somebody's help back. It's just me-, meant,
th-, that again that people added another

00:43:09.790 --> 00:43:14.490
layer or two to their social networks because
they can count on the goodness of strangers

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:19.530
in many cases, or count on the attention of
strangers as they are trying to negotiate

00:43:19.530 --> 00:43:22.400
the world.

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:26.830
The generational story in this is, is pretty
interesting. It's, i-, it, it, those who have

00:43:26.830 --> 00:43:32.880
grown up with these technologies are i-, add
20% to all the data points I gave you before

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:37.230
if you want to talk about people under age
30. They are much more active, much more filtering,

00:43:37.230 --> 00:43:43.700
much more engaged, much more likely to be
concerned about things than, than their elders.

00:43:43.700 --> 00:43:47.930
They are the ones who, and now, obviously
live in a network environment and think of

00:43:47.930 --> 00:43:52.880
the network as this sort of dashboard of their,
not only of the Internet to them, but of their

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:58.740
social world. They check in constantly, they
monitor constantly, they feel they themselves

00:43:58.740 --> 00:44:02.760
are being monitored constantly; many of them
think now that they have an obligation to

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:07.350
their networks to post material, to update
where they are and what's going on and post

00:44:07.350 --> 00:44:09.160
pictures and, and things like that.

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:14.810
So, so, the people now who are under 30 have
a much more expansive sense about what social

00:44:14.810 --> 00:44:18.610
networks can mean and what they, what role
that they play in people's lives, which doesn't

00:44:18.610 --> 00:44:22.740
mean that they don't care about privacy and
sharing and, and all the, the issues related

00:44:22.740 --> 00:44:30.840
to that. It just means they have a different
sense of it and they have a, a sort of a logic

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:34.990
of life that grows out of first, their use
of the Internet, and now the use of their

00:44:34.990 --> 00:44:39.440
mobile phones. That I want to be in touch,
I want to be perpetually in contact because

00:44:39.440 --> 00:44:43.740
that's what these technologies allow me to
be. And that's kind of fun because I like

00:44:43.740 --> 00:44:48.340
my friends, I like to, to be engaged with
my friends.

00:44:48.340 --> 00:44:52.790
And I'm finally going to run through a, a
bunch of questions that we wrestle with which

00:44:52.790 --> 00:44:56.920
sort of the, a series of questions about the
dark side, or issues about the dark side of

00:44:56.920 --> 00:45:00.100
all this life because it's a, it's a pretty
rosy picture that I've been painting because

00:45:00.100 --> 00:45:02.860
people like it, and they say they like it,
and they say they get things out of it. But

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:07.770
there are things to think about and I, I would
invite your attention to these and maybe we

00:45:07.770 --> 00:45:13.590
can think about how we could structure questions
with your data sets that might, might bring

00:45:13.590 --> 00:45:15.530
helpful answers.

00:45:15.530 --> 00:45:19.230
One of the questions is jus-, tech-induced
isolation. There are people who worry that

00:45:19.230 --> 00:45:25.010
this environment is so compelling now that
people will turn to it as a substitute for

00:45:25.010 --> 00:45:29.930
engagement in real life. That people prefer
living in virtual space rather than face-to-face

00:45:29.930 --> 00:45:36.020
space because it's easier, it's less hassle,
it's less threatening in some respects, and

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:39.430
it's just, it's just an easier way to be,
particularly if you're not necessarily the

00:45:39.430 --> 00:45:44.640
most extroverted person. A lot of the data
we see cuts against that. Tha-, that the people

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:48.650
who are the heaviest tech users are also the
most socially engaged, the, have the most,

00:45:48.650 --> 00:45:50.790
the, large-scale and most diverse networks.

00:45:50.790 --> 00:45:55.590
But there is something to, to worry about
that obviously nags at the culture and, and,

00:45:55.590 --> 00:46:01.860
and we get it reflected in our lives a lot
of times. There, obviously there is the privacy

00:46:01.860 --> 00:46:05.490
question. In this environment where so much
is being disclosed and so much is being captured

00:46:05.490 --> 00:46:12.190
and so much can be m-, molded together, there
are ways now that people are anxious about

00:46:12.190 --> 00:46:15.740
the degree to which they are ceding control
of their identity.

00:46:15.740 --> 00:46:20.930
The millennials story in this is a little
bit different. My friend, Dana Boyd, i-, has

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:25.650
the smartest formula, formulation of this.
In the policy sphere in privacy, you talk

00:46:25.650 --> 00:46:30.550
about Personally Identifiable Information,
P-I-I, right? That's the term of art.

00:46:30.550 --> 00:46:37.550
Well, Dana says for kids or for people, you
know, under 30, it's not so much PII as P-E-I;

00:46:37.550 --> 00:46:42.540
they worry about Personally Embarrassing Information.
Their metric for figuring out what to disclose

00:46:42.540 --> 00:46:47.310
or what can come back to bite them is not
necessarily their email address or their cell

00:46:47.310 --> 00:46:50.600
phone number that can be used to text, or
their birthday, which all of them will disclose

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:54.590
under virtually any circumstances. But it's
stuff that's embarrassing that could come

00:46:54.590 --> 00:47:00.530
back to challenge who they are and to make
life more uncomfortable for them as they find

00:47:00.530 --> 00:47:06.410
new employers, find new significant others,
find all sorts of new ways to engage the world

00:47:06.410 --> 00:47:11.470
and so privacy has a somewhat different context
in this, in, in this social networking environment

00:47:11.470 --> 00:47:14.801
than it might have had, especially for Americans,
in the past.

00:47:14.801 --> 00:47:19.750
And then they finally, there's, there's this
sort of biggest series of issues that these

00:47:19.750 --> 00:47:24.130
technologies allow all sorts of great social
interactions and community formation to take

00:47:24.130 --> 00:47:29.810
place. It is indiscriminate about whether
good guys are performing those acts or bad

00:47:29.810 --> 00:47:35.200
guys. Th-, it's just as easy for bad guys
to find new communities of interest and perform

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:40.270
new sort of outreach with these technologies,
recruit new members, gain new things, and

00:47:40.270 --> 00:47:42.310
actually reinforce their belief system.

00:47:42.310 --> 00:47:45.930
And in this environment, it's a lot easier
to find people who think exactly like you

00:47:45.930 --> 00:47:50.830
do. And you can sc-, screen the world in a
way that you don't have contrary information

00:47:50.830 --> 00:47:55.390
